ilArticleApr 1975Int J Rock Mech Min Sci Geomech Abstr N.R. Morgenstern E.C. McrobertsViewPermafrost TerminologyArticleJan 2010 R. J. E. Brown W. O. KupschThe steadily expanding economic developments in northern Canada, accompanied by increasing permafrost investigations for science and engineering, have intensified the need for standarized terminology. The primary list of more than 300 terms was reduced to 184 terms, of which 146 were to be defined and 38 cross-referenced to the defined terms. Added to these for a total of 237 items, were 53 items which are inverse word order listings to achieve alphabetical groupings of related terms. Examples are the \"ice' terms, such as aggradational ice and buried ice, which are listed as ice, aggradational and ice, buried; and the \"permafrost' terms such as contemporary permafrost and continuous permafrost, which are listed as permafrost, contemporary and permafrost, continuous. -from AuthorsViewShow abstractDownloaded from www.nrcresearchpress.com by Huazhong University of Science and Technology on 06J CanSciCan. J. Earth Sci. Downloaded from www.nrcresearchpress.com by Huazhong University of Science and Technology on 06/04/13 For personal use only.Groundwater in permafrost regions of CanadaJan 197483-93Van EverdingenVAN EVERDINGEN, R. 0. 1974. Groundwater in permafrost regions of Canada. In: Permafrost hydrology, Proc. Workshop Seminar, 1974. Can. Nat. Comm. Int. Hy-drol. Decade, pp. 83-93.Temperature and heat flux measurements through permafrost as a geophysical toolJan 197417-27A M JessopA S JudgeJESSOP, A. M. and JUDGE, A. S. 1974. Temperature and heat flux measurements through permafrost as a geophysical tool. Proc. Symp. Permafrost Geophys., Nat. Res. Counc. Can., Tech. Memo. No. 113, p. 17-27.Frost and permafrost definitionsJan 1955107-1F HennionHENNION, F. 1955. Frost and permafrost definitions. U.S. Nat. Res. Counc., Highway Res. Board, Washington, D.C., HRD Bull. 1 1 1, pp. 107-1 10.Permafrost or permanently froze