or emphasis and ease of handling, various subdivisions of geocryology are discussed elsewhere in this volume (q.v. Permafrost, Engineering Geology). Overlap also will be found with other topics (Washburn, 1980). The \u201cworld of ice\u201d is a fascinating place for skiers and others, but a scourge to many. Avalanches from a local overabundance of snow are to be avoided or reduced in their destructiveness by periodic artificial triggering, yet elsewhere techniques are sought to augment snow accumulation for an ultimate increase in water supply. Perennial and seasonal snow and ice modify...This is a preview of subscription content, log in to check access.ReferencesArmy Cold Regions Research and Engineering Laboratory, 1969, Cold Regions Science and Engineering Monograph 1-A.Google ScholarEverdingen, R. O. van, 1976. Geocryological terminology, Canadian Jour. Earth Sci. 3, 862\u2013867.Google ScholarHobbs, P. V., 1974. Ice Physics. Oxford, England: Clarendon Press, 837p.Google ScholarJohn, B. S. (ed.), 1979. The Winters of the World \u2014 Earth under the Icebergs. New York: Wiley, 256p.Google ScholarKingery, W. D. (ed.), 1963. Ice and Snow \u2014 Properties, Processes, and Applications. Cambridge, Mass.: M.I.T. Press, 684p.Google ScholarNational Research Council of Canada, 1978. Proceedings of the Third International Conference on Permafrost, Vols. I and II. Ottawa, 1202p.Google ScholarWashburn, A. L., 1980. Geocryology. New York: Wiley, 406p.Google ScholarCross-references\u00a0Geotechnical Engineering: Remote Sensing, Engineering Geology; Rheology, Soil and Rock.Copyright information\u00a9\u00a0Van Nostrand Reinhold Company Inc.\u00a01984Authors and AffiliationsRobert\u00a0F.\u00a0BlackThere are no affiliations available How to cite Cite this entry as: Black R.F. (1984) Geocryology. In: Finkl C. (eds) Applied Geology. Encyclopedia of Earth Sciences Series, vol 3. Springer, Boston, MA .RIS Papers Reference Manager RefWorks Zotero .ENW EndNote .BIB BibTeX JabRef Mend