 difference, taken without regard to sign, between the values of two variables absolute errorthe difference between the measured or inferred value of a quantity and its actual value. absolute humidity(1) the ratio of the mass of water vapor to the volume occupied by a mixture of water vapor and dry air (2) mass of water contained in a unit volume of moist air. Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology accretiongrowth of a cloud or precipitation particle by the collision and union of a frozen particle (ice crystal or snowflake) with a super-cooled liquid droplet which freezes on impact. Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology accumulationall processes by which snow or ice are added to a glacier, this is typically the accumulation of snow, which is slowly transformed into ice; other accumulation processes can include avalanches, wind-deposited snow, and the freezing of rain within the snow pack.Topic:\u00a0glaciersclimatology and meteorologysnow accumulation areaarea of a glacier where more mass is gained than lost.Topic:\u00a0glaciers accumulation seasonperiod during which a glacier gains more mass than it loses; usually coincides with winter.Topic:\u00a0glaciers accumulation zonearea of a glacier where more mass is gained than lost.Topic:\u00a0glaciers accuracythe extent to which the readings of an instrument approach the true value of the calculated or measured quantities, supposing that all possible corrections are applied. Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology acid precipitationrain or snow containing acidic substances, resulting from the atmospheric pollution mainly with sulfur and nitrogen; acid precipitation has a lower pH than unpolluted rain. Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology active air-cooled thermal pilea foundation pile on which a cold air refrigeration system has been installed to remove heat from the ground. Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost active construction methods in permafrostspecial design and construction methods used for engineering works in permafrost areas where permafrost degradation cannot be prevented.Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost active ice wedgean ice wedge that is growing as a result of repeated (but not necessarily annual) winter cracking.Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost active layerthe layer of ground that is subject to annual thawing and freezing in areas underlain by permafrost; also known as seasonal frost. Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost active liquid refrigerant pilea foundation pile on which a liquid coolant refrigeration system has been installed to remove heat from the ground.Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost active rock glaciera mass of rock fragments and finer material, on a slope, that contains either an ice core or interstitial ice, and shows evidence of present movement.Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrostglaciers active thermokarstthe process by which characteristic landforms are currently developing as a result of thawing of ice-rich permafrost or melting of massive ice. Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost active-layer failurea general term referring to several forms of slope failures or failure mechanisms commonly occurring in the active layer overlying permafrost. Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost active-layer thicknessthe thickness of the layer of the ground that is subject to annual thawing and freeing in areas underlain by permafrost.Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost adfreeze strengththe tensile or shear strength which has to be overcome to separate two objects that are bonded together by ice.Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost adfreeze/adfreezingthe process by which two objects are bonded together by ice formed between them.Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost advancewhen a mountain glacier's terminus extends farther downvalley than before; glacial advance occurs when a glacier flows downvalley faster than the rate of ablation at its terminus. Topic:\u00a0glaciers advectionthe horizontal transfer of air mass properties by the velocity field of the atmosphere. Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology advection fogfog which forms in the lower part of a warm moist air mass moving over a colder surface (land or water). Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology aerosolnon-gaseous substances, divided into solid particles or liquid droplets, held in suspension in the atmosphere. Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology aggradational icethe additional ground ice formed as a direct result of permafrost aggradation. Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost air freezing indexthe cumulative number of degree-days below 0\u00b0 C for the air temperature during a given time period.Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorologyfrozen ground or permafrost air massan extensive body of the atmosphere in which physical properties, particularly temperature and humidity, exhibit only small and continuous differences in the horizontal plane; it may extend over an area of several million square kilometers and over a height of several kilometers. Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology air temperaturethe ambient temperature indicated by a thermometer exposed to the air but sheltered from direct solar radiation, or placed in an instrument shelter 1.5 to two meters above ground; also called surface temperature. Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology air thawing indexthe cumulative number of degree-days above 0\u00b0C for the air temperature during a given period.Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorologyfrozen ground or permafrost Pages1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 9 \u2026 next \u203a last \u00bb Find Data Search NSIDC Data NASA Earthdata Search IceBridge Portal Data Collections List Stay Current Arctic Sea Ice News and Analysis Sea Ice Index (Passive microwave satellite data) MASIE (Daily sea ice extent, multi-source) Greenland Today Newsroom Learn About Snow and Ice Icelights: Answers to Your Questions Cryosphere Quick Facts All About Glaciers All About Snow All About Sea Ice Arctic Climatology - A Primer Get Help Know