| N | O | P | Q | R | S | T | U | V | W | X | Y | Z | all ablation(1) combined processes (such as sublimation, fusion or melting, evaporation) which remove snow or ice from the surface of a glacier or from a snow-field; also used to express the quantity lost by these processes (2) reduction of the water equivalent of a snow cover by melting, evaporation, wind and avalanches. Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorologyglacierssnow ablation areathe area of a glacier where more glacier mass is lost than gained.Topic:\u00a0glaciers ablation hollowsdepressions in the snow surface caused by the sun or warm, gusty wind.Topic:\u00a0glaciers ablation morainemound or layer of moraine in the ablation zone of a glacier; the rock has been plucked from the mountainside by the moving glacier and is melting out on the ice surface.Topic:\u00a0glaciers ablation seasonperiod during which glaciers lose more mass than they gain; usually coincides with summer.Topic:\u00a0glaciers ablation zonearea or zone of a glacier where snow and ice ablation exceed accumulation. Topic:\u00a0glaciers absolute differencethe difference, taken without regard to sign, between the values of two variables absolute errorthe difference between the measured or inferred value of a quantity and its actual value. absolute humidity(1) the ratio of the mass of water vapor to the volume occupied by a mixture of water vapor and dry air (2) mass of water contained in a unit volume of moist air. Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology accretiongrowth of a cloud or precipitation particle by the collision and union of a frozen particle (ice crystal or snowflake) with a super-cooled liquid droplet which freezes on impact. Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology accumulationall processes by which snow or ice are added to a glacier, this is typically the accumulation of snow, which is slowly transformed into ice; other accumulation processes can include avalanches, wind-deposited snow, and the freezing of rain within the snow pack.Topic:\u00a0glaciersclimatology and meteorologysnow accumulation areaarea of a glacier where more mass is gained than lost.Topic:\u00a0glaciers accumulation seasonperiod during which a glacier gains more mass than it loses; usually coincides with winter.Topic:\u00a0glaciers accumulation zonearea of a glacier where more mass is gained than lost.Topic:\u00a0glaciers accuracythe extent to which the readings of an instrument approach the true value of the calculated or measured quantities, supposing that all possible corrections are applied. Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology acid precipitationrain or snow containing acidic substances, resulting from the atmospheric pollution mainly with sulfur and nitrogen; acid precipitation has a lower pH than unpolluted rain. Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology active air-cooled thermal pilea foundation pile on which a cold air refrigeration system has been installed to remove heat from the ground. Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost active construction methods in permafrostspecial design and construction methods used for engineering works in permafrost areas where permafrost degradation cannot be prevented.Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost active ice wedgean ice wedge that is growing as a result of repeated (but not necessarily annual) winter cracking.Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost active layerthe layer of ground that is subject to annual thawing and freezing in areas underlain by permafrost; also known as seasonal frost. Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost active liquid refrigerant pilea foundation pile on which a liquid coolant refrigeration system has been installed to remove heat from the ground.Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost active rock glaciera mass of rock fragments and finer material, on a slope, that contains either an ice core or interstitial ice, and shows evidence of present movement.Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrostglaciers active thermokarstthe process by which characteristic landforms are currently developing as a result of thawing of ice-rich permafrost or melting of massive ice. Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost active-layer failurea general term referring to several forms of slope failures or failure mechanisms commonly occurring in the active layer overlying permafrost. Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost active-layer thicknessthe thickness of the layer of the ground that is subject to annual thawing and freeing in areas underlain by permafrost.Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost adfreeze strengththe tensile or shear strength which has to be overcome to separate two objects that are bonded together by ice.Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost adfreeze/adfreezingthe process by which two objects are bonded together by ice formed between them.Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost advancewhen a mountain glacier's terminus extends farther downvalley than before; glacial advance occurs when a glacier flows downvalley faster than the rate of ablation at its terminus. Topic:\u00a0glaciers advectionthe horizontal transfer of air mass properties by the velocity field of the atmosphere. Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology advection fogfog which forms in the lower part of a warm moist air mass moving over a colder surface (land or water). Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology aerosolnon-gaseous substances, divided into solid particles or liquid droplets, held in suspension in the atmosphere. Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology aggradational icethe additional ground ice formed as a direct result of permafrost aggradation. Topic:\u00a0frozen ground or permafrost air freezing indexthe cumulative number of degree-days below 0\u00b0 C for the air temperature during a given time period.Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorologyfrozen ground or permafrost air massan extensive body of the atmosphere in which physical properties, particularly temperature and humidity, exhibit only small and continuous differences in the horizontal plane; it may extend over an area of several million square kilometers and over a height of several kilometers. Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology air temperaturethe ambient temperature indicated by a thermometer exposed to the air but sheltered from direct solar radiation, or placed in an instrument shelter 1.5 to two meters above ground; also called surface temperature. Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorology air thawing indexthe cumulative number of degree-days above 0\u00b0C for the air temperature during a given period.Topic:\u00a0climatology and meteorologyfrozen ground or permafrost Pages1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 9 \u2026 next \u203a last \u00bb Find Data Search NSIDC Data NASA Earthdata Search IceBridge Portal Data Collections List Stay Current Arctic Sea Ice News and Analysis Sea Ice Index (Passive microwave satellite data) MASIE (Daily sea ice extent, multi-source) Greenland Today Newsroom Learn About Snow and Ice Icelights: Answers to Your Questions Cryosphere Quick Facts All About Glaciers All About Snow All About Sea Ice Arctic Climatology - A Primer Get Help Knowledge Base Etc. Use & Copyright Web Policy Jobs Home | Contact Us\u00a9 2019, National Snow and Ice Data Center :: Advancing knowledge of Earth's frozen regions", "Cryospheric processes | tutor2u Geography tutor2u Subjects Events Job board Shop Company Support Main menu Cart Account Sign in Sign up Our Subjects \u203a Business \u203a Economics \u203a English \u203a Geography \u203a History \u203a Law \u203a Maths \u203a PE \u203a Politics \u203a Psychology \u203a Sociology \u203a Religious Studies Specialist Channels \u203a The Professional Teacher \u203a Beyond the Bike Homepage Our Subjects Business Economics English Geography History Law Maths PE Politics Psychology Sociology Religious Studies Specialist Channels The Professional Teacher Beyond the Bike Events Job Board Shop Company Support Geography Explore Geography Search Go Explore Blog Reference Library Collections Shop Events Jobs Geography Reference library Geography Explore Overview What's new Topics Watch now Blog Reference Library Collections Shop Events Jobs Study notes Cryospheric processes Levels: AS, A Level Exam boards: AQA, Edexcel, OCR, IB, Eduqas, WJEC Print page Share: Share on Facebook Share on Twitter Share on Linkedin Share on Google Share by email Cryospheric processes are the processes involving ice sheets and glaciers. Past events and their impact on cryospheric processes: The last ice advance (60 000 \u2013 20 000 BCE) led to an increase in glacial accumulation (snowfall and increased ice coverage providing extra snow to glaciers and ice sheets) so the global cryospheric store was considerably larger at this point. Global sea level dropped at the same time; by about 120 m at the ice-maximum, although this was a relatively small proportion of total ocean storage. Future events and their impact on cryospheric processesThe accumulation to glaciers and ice sheets (avalanches and snowfall) can vary depending upon global climate change. Recent warming of global climate has reduced accumulation and increased ablation (output) levels. Large volumes of summer meltwater and a reduction in winter accumulation has led to lower storage levels in global ice sheets and glaciers. In some areas of the world, for example in northern Bangladesh, the potential long-term risk is that the glaciers in the Himalayas that feed many of the rivers in the country, will melt completely and then important water supplies will disappear with catastrophic effects for farmers in the country. The impact on drainage basins across the world is potentially very serious, with seasonal river levels dropping due to a lack of meltwater from individual mountain glaciers. Hill slope changes will occur also as individual glaciers will melt completely, depositing their encased material as moraines. Subscribe to email updates from tutor2u Geography Join 1000s of fellow Geography teachers and students all getting the tutor2u Geography team's latest resources and support delivered fresh in their inbox every morning. Subscribe Thanks. You're now subscribed to receive email updates! You can also follow @tutor2uGeog on Twitter, subscribe to our YouTube channel, or join our popular Facebook Groups. Job board Exam markers for GCSE and A-level Geography \u2013 Apply now AQA, Home Print page Share: Share on Facebook Share on Twitter Share on Linkedin Share on Google Share by email Geography Study notes Cryospheric processes Glacial processes Andy Day Andy recently finished being a classroom geographer after 35 years at two schools in East Yorkshire as head of geography, head of the humanities faculty and director of the humanities specialism. He has written extensively about teaching and geography - with articles in the TES, Geography GCSE Wideworld and Teaching Geography. You might also like How Feedbacks within and Between the Water & Carbon Cycles Links to Climate Change Study notes Glacial Systems - Variations between Accumulation and Ablation and Feedback Cycles Study notes Glacial Systems - the Glacial Budget Study notes Glacial Systems - Introduction to The Glacial System Study notes Cold Environments Revision quizzes GCSE Geography Revision Quiz - Glaciation Revision quizzes More Study notes Deforestation Study notes Characteristics of the rural-urban fringe Study notes The Demographic Transition Model (DTM) Study notes Human Intervention in the Carbon Cycle and Mitigating the Impacts of Climate Change Study notes How Changes in the Water & Carbon Cycles Can Have Implications for Life on Earth Study notes How Feedbacks within and Between the Water & Carbon Cycles Links to Climate Change Study notes Natural Resource Issues - Mineral Ores Study notes Geopolitics of Energy Study notes Energy Trade Study notes Energy - Nuclear Study notes All Study notes \u203a Teacher Conferences Geography Teacher National Conference 2019 Join us for the inaugural Geography Teacher National Confer