scipline components are analysed in this paper. We consider that Cryospheric Science is an inevitable product of international research on the earth and environmental changes as well as on human sustainable development. It will not only strengthen the linkage between the cryosphere and other earth spheres by deepening traditional research areas, but will also bring more focus on the critical roles of the cryosphere in interactions between earth spheres, and will enhance the relationship between cryospheric change and climate, ecology, hydrology, surface environment and sustainable development. The disciplinary tree of Cryospheric Science is developed following the mainstream of change-impacts adaptation. The disciplines of Cryospheric Science were teased out against characteristics of traditional branches and the developing interdisciplinary branches of cryosphere elements, which will provide reference to Cryospheric Science as it systematically grows to maturity. Cryospheric Science, cryosphere, change, framework, disciplinary system INTRODUCTION While the term \u2018cryosphere\u2019 is derived from the Greek \u2018kryos\u2019, studies on the cryosphere has accelerated since 1972 when, at the Stockholm Human Environment Conference, the World Meteorological Organization (WMO) proposed the cryosphere as a fifth earth sphere alongside the atmosphere, hydrosphere, lithosphere and biosphere. Cryosphere research has seen unprecedented development around the world since the start of the twenty-first century. Most importantly, the World Climate Research Programmer (WCRP) launched its core \u2018Climate and Cryosphere\u2019 (CliC) plans in 2000 based on the Arctic Climate System Study (ACSYS), and the International Union of Geodesy and Geophysics (IUGG) made the decision in 2007, unprecedented in its 80-year history, of adding a new association\u2014the International Cryospheric Science Association (IACS)\u2014reflecting the important role of the cryosphere in global climate change. Currently, cryosphere research moves on basically two parallel lines [1]. WCRP-CliC has focused on improving the understanding of the physical processes and feedback mechanisms between the cryosphere and the climate system. Among its key goals is increasing quantitative assessment of the components of cryospheric change and their impacts, led by past and future climate changes, to strengthen the observation and monitoring of the cryosphere. The other line of research is the development of the \u2018Cryospheric Science\u2019 discipline, which will construct a systematic science of the cryosphere.Early in 2005, the Arctic Climate Impact Assessment [2] highlighted the need to research cryospheric change on regional or local scales, due to the close relationship between cryospheric change and human sustainable development. Olav and Richard [3] discussed how to integrate all elements of the cryosphere into one. The concept of \u2018Cryospheric Science\u2019 was proposed at the very beginning of WCRP-CliC [4], to integrate research on glaciers, ice sheets, permafrost, sea ice, lake and river ice, and snow into research on one uniform earth layer. Since then, the depth and the range of studies in cryospheric research continue to grow and develop.To understand its vulnerabilities and the likely adverse impact of multiple interactions, we need to better understand the system's ability to adapt. To do this, we need to study its vulnerability on regional and local scales, which will help us better understand the influence of cryospheric change on humanity, and find reasonable ways to adapt to such changes. French and Slaymaker [5], in their report on studies on cold regions in Canada, have highlighted the relationship between changes in the environment of cold regions and humans. Studies on the Arctic cryosphere at local, regional and global scales [6\u201310] focused on the land ice albedo, snow and sea ice; the impact of changes in ice sheets and glaciers on average global sea level, land surface and geochemical processes of permafrost and carbon emissions; fresh water effects of snow, ice and sea ice; ecological effects of lake ice; and hydrological effects of glaciers, etc. An assessment of six potential tipping elements that affect the European climate [11] suggested that five factors, including the Greenland and West Antarctic ice sheets, the North Atlantic thermohaline circulation, Arctic sea ice, Alpine glaciers and stratospheric ozone in the northern hemisphere, are closely related to the cryosphere. An assessment of China's cryosphere [12] found that cryospheric changes have widely affected the climate, water resources, ecology and the land surface (through cryospheric disasters and land erosion), and that confronting and adapting to cryospheric changes are very challenging. The Fifth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC AR5) considered the influence of cryospheric change on five processes: surface energy budget, water cycle, primary productivity, surface gas exchange and sea-level rise [13]. The IPCC AR5 points out that, in many areas, melting snow is changing hydrological processes, affecting water quantity and quality; that snow disasters are increasing in North America; and that the risk of large-scale abnormal events, such as ice sheet disintegration, permafrost methane release and drought, are increasing. Global sea level is projected to rise by 0.45\u20130.82 m during 2081\u20132100 under the RCP8.5 scenario [14]. In the long term, the unstable Greenland ice sheet and the west Antarctic ice sheet are projected to have a huge impact on global sea level. Additionally, CO2 released from permafrost are projected at 180\u2013910 Gt, and the Arctic Ocean will be almost ice-free in September. Big changes are projected for the northern tundra, and there are currently no effective measures to adapt to these changes. Meanwhile, all infrastructure is vulnerable to the freeze\u2013thaw cycle, and transportation facilities are particularly vulnerable in glacier or permafrost regions [15].This synopsis suggests that research on the cryosphere has focused on the interaction between the cryosphere and climate and, in particular, on the impact of cryospheric changes on global sea level and the freshwater cycle, as well as local water resources, ecological processes and the cold regions land surface. Cryospheric research is not only improving its mechanisms and processes, but is also more concerned with the interactions between the cryosphere and other spheres and the effect of the cryosphere on these interactions. This research suggests that cryospheric studies are developing along the change-impacts-adaptation mainstream, which is also the core of Cryospheric Science, and similar to the trend of international studies on environmental changes, such as the \u2018Future Earth\u2019, which integrates many related international plans on global change and sustainable development [16,17].However, many questions still remain, including: what is Cryospheric Science, its connotation and extent, its composition and framework? Although the term \u2018Cryospheric Science\u2019 has been widely used, and the IACS has been established for many years, these issues lack systematic study.In this paper, the current scientific knowledge of the cryosphere is first summarized; an explanation of the connotation of Cryospheric Science is proposed based on an analysis of its concepts and contents; and the framework and disciplines of Cryospheric Science are briefly outlined. This paper will then provide clear concepts for Cryospheric Science research and for the development of the discipline. BASIC CONCEPTS OF CRYOSPHERIC SCIENCE AND INTERACTIONS BETWEEN MULTI-SPHERES Cryosphere and Cryospheric Science Before we list the concepts of Cryospheric Science, we need to outline the development of the concept of the cryosphere itself. The Earth's cryosphere can be seen as a variety of snow and ice formations [18,19] or taken as the earth spheres made of frozen water, including glaciers, ice cover, snow cover, sea ice, lake and river ice, permafrost and solid precipitation, etc. [5,20]. In the Encyclopedia of Astrobiology, the definition of the cryosphere has been expanded to encompass the earth layer with low temperatures and frozen water, which includes cold desert [21]. In the Encyclopedia of the Paleoclimatology and Ancient Environment, the definition of the cryosphere consists of six elements: snow cover, sea ice, permafrost, lake ice and river ice, mountain glaciers, small ice caps and ice in clouds [22].Despite some differences in definitions of the cryosphere, the cryosphere mainly includes glaciers, ice caps, snow cover, sea ice, lake and river ice, and permafrost. The permafrost is one of the most important components, as it is the most widely distributed cryosphere element. The International Permafrost Association (IPA) defines permafrost as rock and soil layers with a temperature at or below 0\u00b0C for at least two continuous years\u2014a definition that depends on temperature only without reference to soil moisture and is contradictory to the definition of the cryosphere as \u2018Earth's surface frozen water\u2019.From these definitions, we can divide the Earth's cryosphere into three types\u2014continental, marine and aerial\u2014according to the dynamic and thermal conditions in the formation, development and geographical distribution of cryosphere elements. The continental cryosphere is entirely composed of land-based elements, including glaciers (and ice sheets), snow and frozen soil (seasonally frozen soil, permafrost and underground ice, but not permafrost under the sea), and lake and river ice. The marine cryosphere includes sea ice, ice shelves, as well as permafrost under the sea. The aerial cryosphere is composed of frozen water in the atmosphere, including snowflakes, ice crystals, etc. Study of the aerial cryosphere also belongs to atmospheric meteorology; it falls at an intersection of two disciplines, but each has different focuses.No exact definition of \u2018Cryospheric Science\u2019 currently exists. However, its research object is relatively clear, and its research scope has become more extensive. Here, Cryospheric Science is defined as the study of the development and evolution of the cryosphere and of mechanisms of interaction between the cryosphere and other earth spheres, especially the impact of the cryosphere on other spheres and human adaptations to that impact. Cryospheric Science includes: (i) the mechanisms of formation, development and evolution of elements of the cryosphere and the interactions between them; (ii) the interaction between the each element and the overall cryosphere and other earth spheres (atmosphere, hydrosphere, lithosphere and biosphere); and (iii) the impact and risk of cryospheric change on other earth spheres and the relationship between the cryosphere and society and sustainable development, especially adaptation and counter measures to address cryospheric changes on global and regional scales (Fig. 1). Figure 1.View largeDownload slideInteraction between the cryosphere and other earth spheres.Figure 1.View largeDownload slideInteraction between the cryosphere and other earth spheres.Note that interaction between the cryosphere and other earth spheres refers to intersections in which the cryosphere plays a major role (Fig. 1). Clearly, the main body of research is the cryosphere and involves only closely interrelated parts, rather than those that are outside the intersections, excluding those studies on the \u2018cryosphere region\u2019 that lack a direct link with the cryosphere itself. Interactions between the cryosphere and other earth spheres Much of the literature on cryosphere research is focused on the laws governing the cryosphere itself, though more and more studies highlight the role of the cryosphere in its interactions with other earth spheres, which is the main driver of rapidly developing cryosphere science. Thus, it is necessary to discuss here the focus of studies on the interactions between the cryosphere and other earth spheres. Cryosphere and atmosphere Interactions between the cryosphere and the atmosphere mainly include the impacts of climate change on the cryosphere and feedback of cryospheric change on the climate. Traditionally in cryosphere research, impacts of climate change on the cryosphere, or the responses of the cryosphere to climate change, are given as the impact of climate change on its formation and evolutionary processes on various spatial and temporal scales. Feedback from the cryosphere to the atmosphere refers to how cryospheric change in turn affects global climate change\u2014the main concern of both Arctic Climate System(ACSYS) and World Climate Research Programme-Climate and Cryosphere (WCRP-CliC) [20]. Implementation of ACSYS and WCRP-CliC plans has promoted rapidly developing studies on the impact of cryospheric changes on climate and deepened the understanding of the feedback of cryospheric change on climate.Important issues in the interaction between the cryosphere and the atmosphere include: understanding the mechanisms of physical processes and feedbacks; improving the simulation and coupling of cryosphere processes into climate or earth system models; and quantitative evaluation of the role of the cryosphere in global and regional climate change, improving the scientific understanding of the climate system and mitigating the uncertainties in climate models. Feedbacks from the cryosphere to the Earth's climate is important in terms of the cryosphere changing the global or regional water balance, which affects global energy and water distribution and eventually leads to global climate change. The effect ranges from variations in snow cover and permafrost that change the land surface energy balance, to impacts of continental ice and sea ice on global albedo and the ocean thermohaline circulation. The spatial scales can be global (both sea and land), hemispheric (e.g. snow cover change in the northern hemisphere), regional (e.g. the Qinghai-Tibet plateau cryosphere, the polar cryosphere) and the temporal scales vary from seasonal, annual, interdecadal to centennial, millennial and even longer [1,13]. The impacts of the cryosphere on climate include [5]: (i) high surface reflectivity (albedo); (ii) the fact that all three phases of water (solid, liquid and vapor) coexist over a range of temperatures and pressures; and (iii) the large amount of latent heat associated with phase changes between water and ice. These suggest that the cryosphere has a strong impact upon surface energy balance. The presence or absence of snow or ice at the global scale is closely linked to temperature differences that affect global winds and the ocean thermohaline circulations. Cryosphere and biosphere Interactions between the cryosphere and biosphere occur both on the land and in the marine environment. Cryospheric changes on land affect the status of soil water and its temperature, and also the temperature, nutrients and quality of water bodies, and thus the ecological system. Changes in terrestrial ecosystems affect the survival of cryospheric components, especially permafrost, which is significantly affected by vegetation\u2014vegetation degradation is not conducive to permafrost maintenance. The cold and fresh water supply from the melting of the cryosphere into the ocean also changes the temperature and salinity of the ocean, which affects not only ocean circulation, but also the marine ecosystem. Plus, sea ice itself is habitat of some special species. Cryospheric changes have particularly important impacts on marine ecosystems in polar regions.The impacts of cryospheric changes on ecosystems and biogeochemical cycles in the Arctic, Antarctic, and plateau and alpine areas have received extensive attention [23\u201338]. Research on cryosphere ecology focuses on the interactions between the cryosphere and the biosphere, the degree to which and how cryospheric change impacts the distribution patterns of terrestrial and marine ecosystems as the climate changes, and whether the impacts have spatial\u2013temporal thresholds [27,39].How, and to what extent, changes in permafrost impact the carbon cycle are also important issues of concern to the scientific community [40]. The permafrost carbon pool is more than twice that of the atmosphere and falls in between the vegetation and soil carbon pools in volume [41]. As the climate warms, permafrost degradation will accelerate losses of carbon from the permafrost [42\u201344]. Because of this, there is increasing concern about and study of the storage, transformation and release rate of carbon in permafrost [45\u201354]. But, because variations in the permafrost carbon pool are influenced by a variety of factors, accurate estimates of changes in it and its influence on global climate have met challenges. How much carbon is likely to be released from permafrost, over what time scale and when the permafrost carbon pool changes from sink to source are critical issues of concern [41,44,55]. How to construct a communication mechanism of permafrost degradation-carbon fluxes-adapted measures between scientists and policy-makers is the focus of future studies [56]. Cryosphere and hydrosphere On a global scale, cryospheric changes cause global sea-level change and also global water-cycle processes. Cryospheric changes impact the ocean\u2013freshwater balance, which drives the ocean thermohaline circulation, and thus global ocean circulation. On a regional or, even more importantly, a catchment scale, cryospheric changes affect hydrological processes not only in the increase or decrease of runoff, but also in its seasonal distribution, thereby affecting the use of water resources.Because of their important role in the global water cycle, studies on cryospheric hydrological processes have received attention [37,40,57,58]. At present, the focus of studies on cryosphere hydrology is mainly on: (i) the impact of changes in glaciers on meltwater and river runoff [36,37,57,58]; (ii) hydrological effects of permafrost [59\u201364]; (iii) impacts of the cryosphere on large-scale hydrological processes [65\u201368]; and (iv) the impacts of climate change on snow hydrology as well as the application of updated remote sensing data and technology and modeling of processes at multiple scales [69\u201378].However, because of the big differences in temporal and spatial scales of the hydrological effect of changes in various cryospheric components (glaciers, ice sheets, snow cover, sea ice, permafrost), there is still a lack of adequate understanding of their complex hydrological effects. Moreover, answering when the long-term meltwater discharge will reach its tipping point is now the focus of attention over the various mountainous regions. The time range of this tipping point for a single glacier can be derived through observation and simulation; however, the sensitivity and response of processes to climate change vary greatly between glaciers, depending on orientation, sizes and topography (e.g. shading) in a basin. Therefore, to determine the glacial meltwater processes and the meltwater tipping point on the basin scale, we need breakthrough innovations in theory, methods and technology [1]. Meanwhile, the physical, chemical and biological processes corresponding to hydrological processes are rarely taken into consideration. Thus, taking the whole cryosphere basin as a study area, future studies will focus on how to systemically consider the hydrological process of each cryospheric element. These include its effect on river runoff, while also considering the hydrological process of various land uses/land covers to provide a reliable basis for accurately analysing the water source, hydrological processes and runoff changes, reducing the uncertainty of forecasting future changes, and improving the precision and capacity for prediction. Cryosphere and lithosphere Studies on interactions between the cryosphere and lithosphere mainly focus on soil erosion and frost-weather alterations. Snow, ice and freeze-thaw-cycle erosion is one of the most striking dynamic processes of the transformation of the lithosphere. Additionally, loose sediments from rapid and intense erosion processes of the cryosphere enable the formation of glacier debris flow and glacial lake outburst floods, which come with high risks to humans [79\u201383].Cryospheric changes have directly shaped land surfaces through freeze\u2013thaw erosion, frost weathering, and transportation and deposition processes, strongly enhancing the formation of surface geomorphology. Modern land surface processes in the cryosphere and in environments in cold regions, and the impacts of climate change on physical, chemical and biological processes in cold regions are very important scientific issues. The long-term impacts of glacial erosion and the process and strength of frost erosion on the environments in these regions are areas of study that should be developed in the future [84,85].Cryospheric changes directly affect the frequency, extent, and spatial and temporal scales of the impact of glacier and permafrost hazards, including glacier lake outburst floods, glacial debris flow, wind-blown snow, avalanches, blizzards, freezing rain, freeze\u2013thaw hazards, and river and sea-ice disasters. The study of cryosphere hazards is focused on formation processes and mechanisms, and the interaction between the environment and the hazard [83,86]. With climate change and rapid economic development, the degree of disaster exposure is higher, thus these hazards are occurring with higher frequency. Studies of their mechanisms and their prediction, as well as early warning and prevention measures, are needed and have become important scientific issues. Risk assessments of potential hazards are also required.In geomorphic terms, mass exchanges of sediment are modulated by the ratio of the mean magnitude of barriers to change (available sediments) to the mean magnitudes of the disturbing forces (e.g. snowmelt runoff, jokulhlaups, glacier erosional power). Cryospheric change induced either by human activity or by natural climate variabilities can generate rapid landscape changes both at the local scale and, in a cumulative sense, at the global scale. Globally, glacial and periglacial mountain environments are vulnerable to the effects of ongoing climate change. Changes in these environments show complex and non-linear responses to climate change, affected by time lags, feedback and antecedent factors, including geologic control and its history. Therefore, future research will focus on the potential change in mountain glaciers and the periglacial environment's response to global warming, as well as the impact of these changes on hydrology and the ecology of the biosphere (biodiversity and ecosystem services, sustainable agriculture and water resources), the human environment (cultural and heritage landscapes and social/economic activities) and the impact on policy and planning downstream [3,84,85]. Cryosphere and anthroposphere The cryosphere is closely related to the anthroposphere. Cryospheric changes not only affect ecology, water resources, the handling, storing and redistribution of land surface materials, but also cryosphere disasters (such as glacial lake outburst floods, heaving and thawing, lake and river ice, wind-blown snow and frozen rain) affect socio-economic development and threaten people's lives and property. Conversely, human activities also affect the status and fate of the cryosphere. Activities such as construction in permafrost areas and resource extraction will accelerate permafrost thawing in the absence of any protection measures. Similarly, glacier tourism promotes the development of the local economy even while it affects the environment of the glacier and might even contribute to accelerating glacier retreat. The influence of the cryosphere spreads from the poles, North and South America, Asia, Europe and Africa, etc., affecting different regions and issues from fresh water and ecology, to various disasters [7,8,10,40].Overall, the cryosphere has both positive and negative effects on natural and societal systems. Positive influences mainly derive from the benefits provided by the cryosphere [86], such as the key roles of the cryosphere in maintaining ecosystems and regulating water resources. The cryosphere is also an important tourism resource [88,89]. Regional energy development, germplasm resources and protection of animal habitat in cryosphere regions can not be separated from the support of cryosphere science, and the unique culture and religion of cryosphere regions are an important part of human civilization [10,90]. To date, the function and values of cryosphere services\u2014the various benefits that human society directly or indirectly derives from the cryosphere, including resources, products and benefits obtained from it\u2014have neither been fully described nor well evaluated [87,91].The negative effects of cryospheric changes are mainly due to cryosphere hazards, such as avalanches, glacier debris flows, meltwater floods, frost swelling and thaw sinking, and the impact of melting and collapse on structure, and the land surface, etc., as well as other negative influences. Among them, the impact of sea-level rise on coastal areas, the impact of Arctic permafrost thawing on coastal erosion, snow hazards and low temperature, snow and ice disasters, the adverse effects of cryospheric changes on ecosystems and the reduction of fresh water from ice and snow resources in arid and mountain areas are the most essential ones.The change in extent and condition of sea ice is likely to impede human access for hunting marine mammals. Although Arctic residents have a history of adapting to change, the complex interlinkage among societal, economic and political factors and climatic and cryospheric stresses represent unprecedented challenges for northern communities, particularly if the rate of change becomes faster than the capability of social systems to adapt [35]. Many species and ecosystems with limited adaptive capacity are subject to very high risks with an additional warming of 2\u00b0C, particularly in the area of the Arctic Ocean covered by sea ice [40].Human adaptation in the context of global climate change typically involves systematic processes, action and the ability to better respond to, manage and adjust to changing conditions, pressures, disasters, risks and opportunities. Studies on adaptation to the effects of cryospheric changes are just beginning, and relevant publications are limited [92]. However, the cryospheric change is only the change of a special part of global change. Concepts of vulnerability, risk, resilience and adaptation to climate change also can directly be used or be a guide to similar studies of the cryosphere [93]. Such studies mainly focus on how to assess the vulnerability and adaptability of the cryosphere itself, then plan for adaptation measures to cryospheric changes for human beings [93\u201397]. Risk assessments on the impact of cryospheric changes and cost\u2013benefit analysis to adapt to the influence of cryospheric changes will be explored (Fig. 2). Figure 2.View largeDownload slideRelationship between the cryosphere and sustainable development.Figure 2.View largeDownload slideRelationship between the cryosphere and sustainable development.With regard to cryospheric benefits, studies are mainly on services (freshwater resources, germplasm resources, etc.), regulation (climate, runoff and ecological regulation), culture (tourism and sports, religions and unique culture) and habitat [87]. New studies will focus on the evolution of the benefits of cryosphere water resources, the tipping point of function changes, the threshold of service function loss, and the industrial structure adjustment path and functional zone to adapt to cryospheric change. Core scientific issues include a methodology framework for studying cryosphere service functions, a method to assess cryosphere dynamic resources, and the quantitative expression and projection of cryosphere service functions. RESEARCH FRAMEWORK AND DISCIPLINES OF CRYOSPHERIC SCIENCE Framework of Cryospheric Science There are three main aspects of Cryospheric Science: cryosphere processes, mechanisms and changes; the impact of cryospheric change; and adaptation to cryospheric change. These gradually advance from basic research to applied basic research, then to applied research, and the effect of the applied research depends on the depth of the scientific understanding of the basic research. The cryosphere scientific research framework can be represented in a Cryospheric Science Tree (CST, Fig. 3). Figure 3.View largeDownload slideSchematic map of Cryospheric Science Tree (CST).Figure 3.View largeDownload slideSchematic map of Cryospheric Science Tree (CST).The first and foremost study of basic research of Cryospheric Science is the energy and water balance processes and mechanisms of the cryosphere (lowest layer of CST). Basic cryosphere research focuses on monitoring the dynamic water and energy mechanisms of its elements, its evolution and current processes, and so on. Applied basic research mainly focuses on the impact of changes in the cryosphere on climate, ecology, hydrology, global sea level, surface processes and on cryosphere-related disasters (third layer of CST). Applied research studies the vulnerability and risk resulting from those changes as well as resilience and adaptation to change, especially with regard to sustainable development on global, regional or local scales (top layer of CST).In summary, along with the development of earth system science, climate change science and sustainable development science, Cryospheric Science itself developed very rapidly; the core issues of Cryospheric Science come from a system perspective to study each element of the cryosphere itself, the relationship between elements, and the relationship between the cryosphere and other earth spheres. The scientific goal of cryosphere science is to understand the natural and anthropogenic processes, mechanisms and impacts and the application of socio-economy to the cryosphere. Cryospheric Science disciplinary structure Cryospheric Science is very interdisciplinary and is related to many earth science branches and beyond, including studies of the atmosphere, hydrosphere, biosphere, lithosphere and anthroposphere. Measures and methods of research include principles and advanced technologies in mathematics, physics, chemistry, biology, humanities and social sciences. The objective of Cryospheric Science is to study not only the cryosphere itself, but also the interactions between the cryosphere and other earth spheres. Therefore, the branches of Cryospheric Science (Fig. 4) are closely related to the subjects of cryospheric elements and the relationship between the cryosphere and the other earth spheres. The development and improvement of these branches will construct the discipline structure of Cryospheric Science. Figure 4.View largeDownload slideDisciplinary structure (system) of Cryospheric Science.Figure 4.View largeDownload slideDisciplinary structure (system) of Cryospheric Science.Mass and energy balance forms the basis of the theory of Cryospheric Science. One of the key processes in the formation and evolutionary processes of the cryosphere is solid\u2013liquid phase transition. When solid ice converts to liquid water in elements of the cryosphere, heat exchange is required. The heat budget process is controlled by the Sun's radiation and the energy balance between the ice surface, ice body and atmosphere. Energy balance is the basic driver underlying glacier advance and retreat, ice sheet change, snow formation and melting, permafrost building and thawing, and sea-ice formation and melting. Movements of cryosphere elements (including phase transition) are continuous; heat and water exchange, solid\u2013liquid phase change and dynamics result in mass changes of the cryosphere itself, leading to the energy or mass changes of other earth spheres. The principle of mass balance is the law of conservation of mass.Traditional cryospheric research involves glaciology; geocryology; Quaternary glaciology; river, lake and sea-ice research; and others. While glaciology includes research on snow, snow is also a major factor to be considered in research on frozen ground and sea ice. Glaciology also includes the studies of lake and river ice.In the study of interactions between the cryosphere and other earth spheres, from the perspective of subject composition, Cryospheric Science includes the disciplines of cryosphere climate, cryosphere hydrology, cryosphere ecology, cryosphere environment and cryosphere sociology. Some of these disciplines are far from mature, but some related issues have received more attention; our understanding and awareness constantly deepen, and the need for system-wide basic and applied scientific studies on the relationship between the cryosphere and other earth spheres has increased greatly. Thus, we propose them as branch disciplines of Cryospheric Science, which not only meets the practical need and trend of the development of international studies, but also the trend for promoting Cryospheric Science systematically grows to maturity.Cryosphere hydrology is relatively developed among the branches of Cryospheric Science. Although the term \u2018cryosphere hydrology\u2019 has not been widely used in international research, glacier hydrology, permafrost hydrology, snow hydrology, as well as other similar disciplines have had a long history [98] and the similar term \u2018cold region hydrology\u2019 is already widely used. The book entitled Permafrost Hydrology [98] covers not only permafrost hydrology, but also snow cover, glaciers, lake and river ice, wetlands in cold regions, as well as cryosphere hydrological processes, which actually reflects the underlying idea of \u2018cryosphere hydrology\u2019.In comparison with cryosphere hydrology, cryosphere ecology, cryosphere environment and cryosphere sociology, although developed to different degrees, are still in an early stage of development as systematic disciplines. This is especially true of cryosphere sociology, whose research subject of social and economic sustainable development in areas impacted by cryospheric changes has only recently become an area of concern, and has limited literature.The basic disciplines of Cryospheric Science include geography, atmospheric sciences, geomorphology, hydrology, ecology, environment and sociology. Advanced technology and computer technology, in particular remote sensing (RS), Geographic Information Systems (GIS) and Global Positioning System (GPS) technology, play an important role in promoting Cryospheric Science. Cryospheric Science belongs to basic and applied basic science, and is also a new discipline of comprehensive natural science and social science. Perspective on Cryospheric Science At present, climate change, environmental change, earth system science and sustainable development, which, by their nature, must encompass the terms \u2018comprehensive\u2019 and \u2018system\u2019, have become foci of concern and hot spots of the international research community. These issues differ from important issues of the past primarily in their greater concern with the sustainable development of human society. They have deep connections with each other\u2014although each has its own concerns, they all have many things in common.Future studies of global change will be more systematic and comprehensive and will address sustainable development. Within this context, Cryospheric Science should address the major science problems of today. They will be carried out in a systematic way, from determining cryosphere dynamic processes and the mechanism of the impact of cryospheric changes to adaptation to cryospheric changes. Moreover, this will be accomplished by combining natural and human processes to develop in-depth awareness of cryosphere natural processes, and seeking adaptive science countermeasures for sustainable development.The frontiers of Cryospheric Science are summarized in Fig. 5, including: Deepen the understanding of the mechanisms of the cryosphere itself, at different spatial and temporal scales, including dynamic, water and energy processes and response to change, to more accurately forecast potential changes in cryosphere elements and provide a reliable basis for understanding the impact of cryospheric change. Improved modeling capacity is needed for the cryosphere as part of the weather/climate system in studies on interactions between the cryosphere and atmosphere, including how the cryosphere affects weather/climate systems at global, regional and local scales and at various time scales. Accessing these effects will require a quantitative and detailed description of the cryosphere elements in the weather/climate system.Understand the impact of the cryosphere on the global water cycle and on regional water resources, including more attention on how the cryosphere influences sea-level changes and global ocean circulation; and how cryospheric changes impact hydrological processes and catchment scale sustainable water resource utilization. This requires deepening our understanding of levels of the cryosphere in the global water-cycle process and the impact of cryospheric changes on the utilization of water resources in a catchment.Reveal the interaction between the cryosphere and biosphere and carbon cycle, including not only impacts of cryospheric change on terrestrial ecosystems, but also impacts on marine ecosystems. Exchange of greenhouse gases between cryosphere elements, especially permafrost, should be the next focus of attention. The threshold of the impact of cryospheric changes on ecosystems at various spatial and temporal scales and the quantitative assessment of greenhouse gas emissions in permafrost are limited by relatively lacking basic research of Cryospheric Science. To improve our knowledge of the way in which the cryosphere and biosphere interact, we need to reveal the relationships between the cryosphere and the biosphere and clarify the permafrost carbon cycle.Quantify the integration effect of earth surface processes on basins and improve our ability to predict disasters. In the interactions between the cryosphere and the lithosphere, the role of cryosphere elements in the land surface is described in physical, chemical, biological and other terms. Along with hazards, including glacier lake outburst floods, freeze\u2013thaw destruction, snowmelt floods, landslide and debris flow increases, cryospheric change strengthens cryosphere-related land surface processes. Future research on the interaction between the cryosphere and the lithosphere should include: (i) developing more accurate warnings and predictions capacity of risk of these hazards; (ii) enhanced sediment-handling capacity under accelerated freeze\u2013thaw erosion, increased thermal thawing of lakes and pools, and increased glacier meltwater and biological processes that result from changes in land surface water and energy\u2014these changes in surface process will lead to changes in physical, biological and geochemical processes. Quantifying and evaluating the impacts of these changes downstream in basin will be a future focus of study.Explore potential approaches to adapting to risks. The focus of interaction between the cryosphere and anthroposphere is how to deal with the impact of changes in the cryosphere, or how human society can adapt to the disadvantages resulting from cryospheric change. A big concern is how large of a negative impact cryospheric changes will have on human society. This scientific issue involves risk assessment: we need to quantify the risk of adverse effects of cryospheric changes on human society in different fields of activity or different industrial areas. Therefore, we need to identify the different effects of different elements of the cryosphere, construct a system and methods of risk evaluation, and explore ways of dealing with these risks. Meanwhile, cryospheric changes benefit human society at certain spatial and temporal scales. The cryosphere itself provides many benefits and has values. Future search priorities include a comprehensive analysis to understand and evaluate the services and values of the cryosphere, conduct quantitative analysis of the risks from cryospheric change and explore ways to adapt to the impacts of that change [87]. Figure 5.View largeDownload slideSchematic map of the frontiers of Cryospheric Science.Figure 5.View largeDownload slideSchematic map of the frontiers of Cryospheric Science. ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS We thank two anonymous reviewers for valuable comments and suggestions that significantly improved this manuscript. This work is supported by the Global Change Research Program of China (2013CBA01808) and the China National Natural Science Foundation (41421061 and L1524012). REFERENCES 1.Ding YJ, Xiao CD. Challenges in the study of cryospheric changes and their impacts [in Chinese with English abstract]. Adv Earth Sci\u00a0 2013; 28: 1067\u201376.2.ACIA. Arctic Climate Impact Assessment\u00a0. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2005.3.Olav S, Richard K. The Cryosphere and Global Environmental Change\u00a0. Blackwell Publishing, 2007.4.CliC. http://clic.npopar.no/, 2012.5.French HM, Slaymaker O. Changing Cold Environments: A Canadian Perspective\u00a0. Chichester, UK: John Wiley & Sons, 2011.Google ScholarCrossrefSearch ADS \u00a06.Paepe R. Cyclic evolution of man and permafrost: the role of permafrost on soc