ht). They are similar to soils of the Organic order in terms of the diagnostic thickness of the organic layers, but they also have permafrost within 1 m of the surface. Generally, there is no evidence of cryoturbation in soils of this great group. Turbic Cryosol Great Group The soils of Turbic great group are characterized by the marked evidence of cryoturbation. Within the soil pit, this will appear as irregular or broken horizons and evidence of mixing of the horizons. At the soil surface, this may also appear as patterned ground. Given the instability associated with actively turbic sites, surface vegetation may be minimal or completely absent, with parent material evident right at the soil surface. Static Cryosol Great Group Static Cryosols are mineral soils without evidence of cryoturbation. They are distinguished from similar soils of other orders (such as Brunisols) by the presence of permafrost within 1 m of the surface. They commonly occur in association with the other two great groups but tend to be found in portions of the landscape with very coarse or recently deposited parent material and/or low moisture levels inhibit the development of turbic features. Leave a Reply Cancel replyYou must be logged in to post a comment. Soil Orders Brunisol Sombric (3) 1-01 Orthic Sombric Brunisol 1-02 Eluviated Sombric Brunisol 1-03 Gleyed Sombric Brunisol Melanic (5) 1-04 Orthic Melanic Brunisol 1-05 Orthic Melanic Brunisol 1-06 Orthic Melanic Brunisol 1-07 Orthic Melanic Brunisol 1-08 Gleyed Melanic Brunisol Eutric (11) 1-09 Orthic Eutric Brunisol 1-10 Orthic Eutric Brunisol 1-11 Orthic Eutric Brunisol 1-13 Orthic Eutric Brunisol 1-14 Orthic Eutric Brunisol 1-15 Orthic Eutric Brunisol 1-16 Eluviated Eutric Brunisol 1-17 Eluviated Eutric Brunisol 1-18 Eluviated Eutric Brunisol 1-19 Eluviated Eutric Brunisol 1-21 Degraded Eutric Brunisol Dystric (1) 1-20 Orthic Dystric Brunisol Chernozem Black (7) 2-01 Orthic Black Chernozem 2-02 Orthic Black Chernozem 2-03 Orthic Blac