Siemon W. Muller (1900-1970) from perm(anent) frost.Show MoreOnline Etymology Dictionary, \u00a9 2010 Douglas Harperpermafrost in Sciencepermafrost[p\u00fbr\u2032m\u0259-fr\u00f4st\u2032]A layer of soil or bedrock that has been continuously frozen for at least two years and as long as tens of thousands of years. Permafrost can reach depths of up to 1,524 m (4,999 ft). It is found throughout most of the polar regions and underlies about one fifth of the Earth's land surface.Show MoreThe American Heritage\u00ae Science Dictionary Copyright \u00a9 2011. Published by Houghton Mifflin Harcourt Publishing Company. All rights reserved.Others Are ReadingWhat Does Gender Really Mean?The Year's Top Word TrendsWord of the DayvolubleWords We Get Wrong: How Many of These Can You Say?Did You Know Real People Write the Dictionary?Nearby words for permafrostperma-perma-pressperma-tanpermaculturepermadeathpermafrostpermafrost tablepermalinkpermalloypermanencepermanencyBrowse the Dictionary:#ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZBrowse by Category:SlangEmojiAcronymsPop CultureMoreAboutCareersContact UsCookies, Terms, & Privacy\u00a9 2019 Dictionary.com, LLC", "Permafrost Home News Weather Entertainment Sports Money More > Lifestyle Health & Fitness Food & Drink Travel Autos Video Kids entertainment You are using an older browser version. Please use a supported version for the best MSN experience. SETTINGS OFF HD HQ SD LO AFP Permafrost Duration: 01:03 6/10/2015 SHARE SHARE TWEET SHARE EMAIL Scientists have called for action to defuse a time bomb of Arctic greenhouse gas as negotiators at UN talks grappled over a climate rescue pact. About 1,500 billion tonnes of heat-trapping carbon gas are estimated to be locked in permafrost, which is thawing as the climate warms, according to new research.VIDEOGRAPHIC UP NEXT NOW PLAYING: other Permafrost AFP UP NEXT Is shale oil drilling a Ponzi scheme? CNBC Britt Robertson Discusses The Second Season Of \"For the People\" AOL Build How \"For The People\" Ha